text=:Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity%0a:Essential: {Category.MorphosyntacticDiversity$:essential}%0a:Title: Linguistics is so cool anymore%0a:Author: ruiranx%0a:Section: F%0a:Completed: 10.04.2021 - 19:37%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210505-214241-868450#%0a* [-05.05.2021 - 14:42-] || TA_mason marked as complete%0a#foxend 210505-214241-868450#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aAn examination of the word "anymore" used in a non-negative context%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aIn standard English, the word "anymore" is known as a negative polarity item (NPI), which means it appears in negative contexts. For example, consider the sentences "I don't even know anymore" and "this doesn't make sense anymore".%0a%0aHowever, across the United States, "anymore" can be used in a positive context so that its meaning is similar to the word "nowadays". For example, consider the following examples[1].%0a%0a- Anymore, John smokes.%0a- You stay in your office too late anymore.%0a%0aThese would both make sense in the context of standard English when "anymore" is substituted with "nowadays".%0a%0a- Nowadays, John smokes.%0a- You stay in your office too late nowadays.%0a%0aIt's worth noting that this positive kind of "anymore" can only be used in present tense, precisely because its meaning is analogous to "nowadays". To highlight this point, consider the following variants on the second example from before.%0a%0a- You stayed in your office too late anymore.%0a- You stayed in your office too late nowadays.%0a%0a- You will stay in your office too late anymore.%0a- You will stay in your office too late nowadays.%0a%0aLinguists assert that usage of the positive "anymore" is fairly scattered, but also somewhat clustered in the Midwest[2]. Furthermore, research suggests that this construct is of Scots-Irish origin [3].%0a%0a[1] https://ygdp.yale.edu/phenomena/positive-anymore%0a[2] https://schwa.byu.edu/files/2014/11/F2013-Reynolds.pdf%0a[3] https://twpl.library.utoronto.ca/index.php/twpl/article/download/6249/3237/%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_mason:)
